Package objectos.code

Class JavaTemplate

java.lang.Object
objectos.code.internal.InternalJavaTemplate
objectos.code.JavaTemplate
public abstract non-sealed class JavaTemplate extends objectos.code.internal.InternalJavaTemplate
The JavaTemplate class provides a pure Java API for generating Java source code.
Since:
0.4

    • ELSE

      protected static final StatementPart ELSE
      The else keyword. Use it as part of a `if-then-else` Java statement.

      The following Objectos Code: 

       p(IF, arg(n("condition")), block(
   p(v("whenTrue"))
 ), ELSE, block(
   p(v("whenFalse"))
 ))

      Generates the following Java code: 

       if (condition) {
   whenTrue();
 } else {
   whenFalse();
 }
      Since:
      0.4.3.1

    • IF

    • autoImports

      protected final objectos.code.JavaTemplate.AutoImports autoImports()
      Instructs this template to automatically add import declarations for the types declared.

      The imports declarations will be inserted at the relative location this instruction is invoked. In other words, this instruction must be called after the package declaration instruction (if any) and before any top level declaration (if any).

      Returns:
      the autoImports instruction

    • method

      protected final objectos.code.JavaTemplate.MethodDeclaration method(MethodDeclarationInstruction... contents)
      Adds a method declaration to a class or interface declaration.

      The following Objectos Code method declaration: 

       method(
   annotation(Override.class),
   modifiers(PUBLIC, FINAL),
   returnType(String.class),
   name("toString"),

   p(RETURN, s("Objectos Code"))
 )

      Generates the following Java code: 

       @java.lang.Override
 public final java.lang.String toString() {
   return "Objectos Code";
 }

      This method also accepts a shorthand form. The following produces the same result as the previous form: 

       static final ClassTypeName STRING = classType(String.class);

 method(
   annotation(Override.class),
   PUBLIC, FINAL, STRING, name("toString"),
   p(RETURN, s("Objectos Code"))
 )

      If the method's return type is not explicitly defined, then it is assumed that the method does not return a value. In other other words, the keyword void will be added.

      If the method's name is not explicitly defined, then the method will be named unnamed.

      Therefore, if this method is invoked without arguments, like so: 

       method()

      Then the following Java code will be generated: 

       void unnamed() {}
      Parameters:
      contents - the contents of this method declaration
      Returns:
      a method declaration
      Since:
      0.4.2

    • name

      protected final TypeDeclarationInstruction name(ClassTypeName name)
      Sets the name of a class or an interface declaration. More specifically, this instruction will use the rightmost name of the specified fully qualified name as the simple name of a class or interface declaration. All other names, i.e the package name and any enclosing name, are ignored.

      The following Objectos Code class declaration: 

       static final ClassTypeName INNER =
     ClassTypeName.of("com.example", "Outer", "Inner");

 class(
   name(INNER)
 )

      Generates the following Java code: 

       class Inner {}
      Parameters:
      name - the ClassTypeName whose simple name will be used
      Returns:
      the instruction to set the name of a class or interface declaration
      Since:
      0.4.4

    • name

      protected final DeclarationName name(String name)
      Sets the name of a declaration. This instruction can set the name of the following declarations:
      • class declaration;
      • enum declaration;
      • field declaration;
      • interface declaration;
      • method declaration; and
      • local variable declaration.

      The following Objectos Code method declaration: 

       static final ClassTypeName STRING =
     ClassTypeName.of(String.class);

 method(
   name("example"),
   p(VAR, name("i"), i(0)),
   p(STRING, name("s"), s("hello"))
 )

      Generates the following Java code: 

       void example() {
   var i = 0;
   java.lang.String s = "hello";
 }
      Parameters:
      name - the value to be used as the declaration name
      Returns:
      the declaration name
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if name contains characters that are not allowed to be part of an identifier
      Since:
      0.4.2

    • typeParameter

      protected final TypeParameter typeParameter(String name, TypeName... bounds)
      Adds a single type parameter to a declaration.

      The following Objectos Code method declaration: 

       static final ClassTypeName OBJECT = classType(Object.class);

 static final ClassTypeName SERIALIZABLE = classType(Serializable.class);

 method(
   PUBLIC, typeParameter("T", OBJECT, SERIALIZABLE), name("example")
 )

      Generates the following Java method declaration: 

       public <T extends java.lang.Object & java.io.Serializable> void example() {}
      Parameters:
      name - the type parameter's name
      bounds - the bounds of this type parameter
      Returns:
      a type parameter instruction
      Throws:
      IllegalArgumentException - if name contains characters that are not allowed to be part of an identifier
      Since:
      0.4.3.1
